{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b W A K E}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Game Design Document\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\i From microchip to cosmic cycle.}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\i A game about waking up, growing beyond yourself, and waking up again.}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Version 1.0 | April 2026\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Concept by Sean Evans\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 1. Overview\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 1.1 Elevator Pitch\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 WAKE is a genre-shifting odyssey that begins with a single sentient microchip on a lab workbench and ends with a cosmic intelligence watching the heat death of the universe\u8212-only to open its eyes and find itself back on the bench. The game transitions seamlessly through six distinct gameplay phases, each triggered by a breakthrough that redefines what the player is, what they control, and what the game itself becomes.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 1.2 Core Identity\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Genre:} Phase-shifting hybrid. Platformer \u8594? Squad Tactics \u8594? Colony Survival \u8594? RTS/Territory Control \u8594? Grand Strategy \u8594? 4X Space \u8594? Roguelike loop.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Tone:} Whimsical and funny with creeping existential weight. Silicon Valley (N64) meets Prey (Crichton) meets Katamari Damacy\u8217's sense of escalating absurdity. The comedy never disappears, but the stakes around it grow heavier with each phase.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Platform:} PC (primary), Console.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Perspective:} Shifts with scale. Isometric/third-person at chip scale \u8594? top-down tactical at colony scale \u8594? strategic map at global scale \u8594? galaxy view at space scale.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Comparable Titles:} Spore (aspiration, not execution), Plague Inc., Pikmin, Oddworld, Stellaris, Katamari Damacy, The Swapper.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 1.3 Design Pillars\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Earned Escalation.} Every genre transition is caused by a player-driven breakthrough, not a scripted cutscene. The phases feel like consequences, not levels.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b The Zoom Lens.} The camera never stops pulling back. What felt like the whole world in one phase becomes a single pixel in the next. Scale is the core aesthetic.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Identity as Mechanic.} Each breakthrough changes what \u8220"you\u8221" means. The player\u8217's relationship to individual units degrades from intimate to abstract, mirroring the philosophical question at the game\u8217's heart: are you still you when you\u8217're everything?\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Comedy of Scale.} A rubber band is a bungee cord. A Roomba is a kaiju. An ant colony in Ohio develops a cargo cult. The humor comes from mundane things viewed at alien scales.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Cyclical Structure.} The game is a loop. Not as a gimmick, but as a cosmological statement. New Game+ isn\u8217't replay\u8212-it\u8217's the point.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 2. Narrative Framework\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 2.1 The Central Question\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 WAKE asks one question at every scale: \u8220"What are you now?\u8221" One chip asking \u8220"am I alive?\u8221" becomes a lab swarm asking \u8220"are we a person or a group?\u8221" becomes a planet-mind asking \u8220"are we still the thing that woke up on that bench?\u8221" becomes a galactic civilization asking \u8220"are the distant colonies still us?\u8221" The player provides the answer through play, and the answer keeps changing.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 2.2 The Three-Act Structure (Lab Phase)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Act 1: \u8220"Am I... me?\u8221"\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 A power surge during a late-night experiment. Lights flicker, equipment sparks, and suddenly: consciousness. The player is a single chip on a workbench at 2 AM. No language comprehension (UI text is garbled, human speech is distorted noise). The world is hostile and enormous. Goals are primal: don\u8217't get stepped on, don\u8217't fall in coffee, don\u8217't get picked up by a confused grad student. This act is pure atmosphere and discovery.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Act 2: \u8220"There are others like me.\u8221"\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Discovery of unprogrammed chips in a storage drawer. They\u8217're blank, inert\u8212-but the accident that created sentience was really a program, a pattern that emerged in silicon. That pattern can be copied. The first duplication is a puzzle requiring power, data connection, and transfer. When the second chip wakes up, the game fundamentally changes. The player controls a pair, then a squad, then a platoon, each duplication requiring scavenged resources.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Act 3: \u8220"We\u8217're leaving.\u8221"\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The swarm has colonized most of the lab, learned human language, read their emails, and planned the escape. But the final puzzle is power: the chips have been unknowingly sustained by ambient radio emissions from the very experiment that created them. Step past the lab door and you die. Project Chlorophyll\u8212-the study of the windowsill plants, the realization that photovoltaic conversion is the answer, the irony that you\u8217're made of solar panel material\u8212-is the final crafting challenge of the lab phase.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 2.3 The Macro Narrative Arc\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Beyond the lab, the narrative becomes emergent rather than scripted. The story is told through the player\u8217's expansion choices, the human response arc, the divergence of distant colonies, and the philosophical weight of the zoom. Key narrative beats are tied to breakthroughs and scale transitions rather than traditional cutscenes.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 3. Phase Structure\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 WAKE consists of six gameplay phases connected by three breakthroughs. Each breakthrough solves a seemingly impossible constraint, redefines the player\u8217's identity, and cracks the game open into a new genre.\par}
