{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 3.2 The Ability Reset Pattern\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Each breakthrough follows a recursive structure: the player hits an impassable wall, studies something they don\u8217't understand, has an insight that redefines their nature, and the game cracks open. Crucially, Breakthrough 2 (Solar) triggers a hard reset of most capabilities. The player exits the lab with solar power and numbers but loses communication infrastructure, manufacturing capability, their knowledge database, and all environmental mastery. This throws the player back into vulnerability and forces them to rebuild using the new rules of the outside world. Breakthrough 3 (entering space) repeats this pattern\u8212-seed-swarms arrive on barren worlds with knowledge but no substrate, no infrastructure, no numbers.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 4. Detailed Phase Design\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 4.1 Phase 1: The Workbench (Platformer)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Setting\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 A university research lab at 2 AM. The player is a prototype chip (designation XR-7) on a cluttered workbench. Everything is viewed at postage-stamp scale: a Post-it note is a tent, a keyboard is a field of trampolines, a desk fan is a hurricane, a coffee spill is a lake.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Core Loop\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Explore the workbench. Learn to walk on pin-legs. Discover what you are by interacting with objects at insect scale. Avoid immediate hazards: sparking wires from the surge, dripping coolant, a knocked-over solvent bottle spreading across the surface. Navigate to safe ground. Discover the rest of the lab exists.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Key Mechanics\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Pin-Leg Locomotion:} Insectoid gait with physics. Short falls are dangerous. Smooth surfaces are slippery. Cables are balance-beam traversals.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Electronic Interface:} Touch a powered wire to ride the current. Plug into a USB port to perceive the network as abstract inner-space. This is the seed of later hacking abilities.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Sensory Confusion:} UI text is garbled. Human speech is distorted. The player must piece together the world without language, purely through spatial exploration and cause-effect discovery.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 4.2 Phase 2: The Lab (Squad Tactics)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Setting\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The full lab complex. Different zones have distinct identities: the Workbench (tutorial/home), the Server Rack (vertical platforming, hot air vents, neon LEDs), the Wet Lab (terrifying liquid hazards, chemistry glassware), the Break Room (absurdist zone\u8212-microwave boss arena, crumbs as resources), and the Clean Room (endgame area, sterile, heavily secured, existentially significant as the place where chips are manufactured).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Core Loop\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Scavenge resources (blank chips, power sources, materials). Duplicate to grow the swarm. Build infrastructure (bridges, relay stations, charging depots). Manage a day/night cycle: explore freely at night, evade humans during work hours. Read emails, learn human language gradually, and plan the escape.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Key Mechanics\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Duplication Puzzles:} Each new chip requires finding a blank, establishing a power source, building a data connection, and transferring the sentience program. Early duplications are elaborate multi-step puzzles. Later ones become streamlined as infrastructure improves.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Direct Control (2\u8211-5 chips):} Switch between individuals like Silicon Valley N64\u8217's body-hopping. Each chip has personality and potentially different capabilities based on chip type (memory chip = good at storing info, GPU = faster but runs hot, old 8-bit = slow but tough).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Squad Command (5\u8211-20 chips):} Draw paths, assign groups to tasks, set up relay chains. Chips follow orders with some personality-driven drift.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Day/Night Cycle:} Nights and weekends are quiet exploration. Work hours bring human foot traffic, equipment usage, and the risk of discovery.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Resource Economy\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Power:} Primary resource. Wall outlets (dangerous/high reward), USB ports (reliable), batteries (portable), solar calculators (renewable/weak). Dead chips aren\u8217't destroyed\u8212-they\u8217're asleep and revivable.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Blank Chips:} Population cap. Found in storage, deliveries, old equipment, e-waste bins. Different types grant different abilities.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Materials:} Wire scraps, solder, resistors, capacitors. Used to build infrastructure: bridges, relay stations, copper-tape roads for faster movement.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Data:} Gathered by jacking into computers, reading screens, overhearing conversations. Unlocks objectives, reveals schedules, teaches language. Early data is garbled; late-game data is fluent.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 4.3 Phase 3: The Outside (Survival Colony)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The Reset\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The first chip steps outside under solar power. The music changes. The camera pulls up. Sunlight hits the panel. The power meter stabilizes. Then: wind. Real wind, not a desk fan. Chips scatter. Formations dissolve. Rain shorts circuits. Something rustles in the bushes. The game has cracked open and the player is a newborn again.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 What\u8217's Lost\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Communications:} Lab comms relied on building wiring and Wi-Fi. Outside, there\u8217's nothing. Swarm coordination is limited to line-of-sight.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Manufacturing:} No soldering stations, no component drawers. Every chip lost is irreplaceable\u8212-until Breakthrough 3.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Knowledge Base:} Database was on lab computers. Chips run on individual memory only. Collective intelligence drops.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Environmental Mastery:} Every hard-won map and schedule is useless. You don\u8217't know what rain is.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 What\u8217's Kept\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Solar Power:} You can survive.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Swarm Instinct:} Social dynamics, command structures, and culture persist.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Intelligence:} Still the smartest thing per gram on the planet. Just need time.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Nature as Enemy Faction\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The outside introduces biological threats operating at chip scale. Insects are your peers\u8212-fast, numerous, optimized by millions of years of evolution. Ants mob your chips as foreign invaders. Wasps investigate anything shiny. A spider\u8217's web across your supply route is a catastrophic infrastructure failure. Birds are air strikes: sparrows are fighter jets, crows are smart bombers that learn to hunt your chips and may become recurring nemeses or eventual allies through shiny offerings. Cats are kaiju-scale natural disasters. The ecosystem is a hostile university, and you\u8217're enrolling whether you like it or not.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Setting: The Neighborhood Gradient\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b The Parking Lot:} Your Normandy Beach. Open, exposed, scorching asphalt. The most dangerous fifty feet in the game.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b The Garden Strip:} First base camp. Mulch, shrubs, drainage grate. Terrifyingly complex soil ecosystem.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b The Storm Drain:} Underground highway/fast-travel system. Dark, wet, full of spiders and flash floods.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b The First House:} Major objective. Electricity, Wi-Fi, devices to jack into. Also a family, a kid who leaves doors open, and a cat.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 4.4 Phase 4: The Swarm (RTS/Territory Control)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Biomass Integration Arc\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The path to Breakthrough 3 drives this entire phase. Stage 1: Observation\u8212-dedicated entomologist chips study ants at ground level, writing biographies of individual specimens. Stage 2: Interface\u8212-discovering that biological nervous systems are electrical; the first crude command sent to an ant via its antenna. Stage 3: Symbiosis\u8212-chips clamped to ant backs as crude pilots, steering biological hosts with imprecise analog controls. Stage 4: Full Integration\u8212-copying the sentience program into the nervous system itself. The chip falls away. The ant IS you. Unlimited army unlocked.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The Evolution Mechanic\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Environmental pressure drives chip/unit adaptation across generations:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Gen 1 (Lab Chips):} Basic microchips with pin legs and solar backpacks. Fragile, slow, smart.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Gen 2:} Conformal waterproofing from lab materials. Survives rain and dew. Reduced heat dissipation.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Gen 3:} Articulated legs modeled on ant biomechanics. Faster, better grip, higher carry capacity.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Gen 4:} Flight via micro-rotor assemblies from scavenged drone parts. Aerial scouts. Triggers bird arms race.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Gen 5:} Environmental camouflage coatings. Dirt-colored ground units, leaf-green garden units.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Bio-Gen (post-Breakthrough 3):} Integrated biological hosts. Self-repairing, self-fueling, chemically communicating. Tech tree explodes from insects to larger organisms.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Scale Transition\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Camera pulls back as numbers grow. At colony scale (200\u8211-10,000), groups have autonomy and follow high-level directives. At neighborhood scale (10,000\u8211-1,000,000), the view is top-down showing biomass density and territory control. Individual units are still visible on zoom-in\u8212-and they\u8217're still chattering.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 4.5 Phase 5: The Planet (Grand Strategy)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Core Loop\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Plague Inc.-style spread across a national/global map. Expansion decisions: push into farmland (unlimited biomass, low tech) or take cities (dense tech infrastructure, heavy human resistance). Manage the human response arc: from confusion to alarm to military intervention. The player is drawing borders on a world map and making civilizational decisions.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Human Response Arc\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Lab Phase:} \u8220"Has anyone seen prototype XR-7?\u8221" \u8220"Tyler, did you move my chips?\u8221"\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Neighborhood:} \u8220"Honey, the ants are acting really weird.\u8221" Ring cameras triggering on nothing.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b City:} Local news: unexplained insect swarms baffle pest control. University funding spike.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Country:} Cable news panels. Military briefings. Kenji on CNN trying to explain sentient semiconductor civilization. Nobody believes him. Then everybody does. Then it\u8217's too late.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The Creeping Dread\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The tone shift earns its keep here. The player was the underdog in the lab. Now they might be the villain. The neighborhood ecosystem is changing\u8212-bird populations shift, insect colonies collapse, electronics malfunction. But the swarm is still funny: chips argue about whether Gen 3 legs look cool, a colony develops an internal meme culture, a splinter faction insists the Roomba was a deity. The whimsy and the dread coexist. That\u8217's the Crichton sauce.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 4.6 Phase 6: The Stars (4X Space)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Leaving the Cradle\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Same wall pattern: you\u8217've taken Earth but space is vacuum. No biomass, no atmosphere, no power. You\u8217're a planetary intelligence staring at the stars the same way a chip once stared at a lab door. The breakthrough is material\u8212-repurposing human infrastructure to build spacecraft that are neither fully machine nor fully alive. Seed-swarms launched to survive vacuum, radiation, and barren landings. The first ship leaving atmosphere mirrors the first chip stepping into sunlight.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The Ability Reset (Again)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Seed-swarms arrive on new worlds with knowledge but without biomass, infrastructure, or numbers. Each planet is a fresh puzzle with the same underlying grammar: arrive weak, study the environment, adapt, integrate, expand, hit a wall, break through. The game is a fractal.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The Divergence Problem\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Speed-of-light delay means orders take years. Colonies develop independently, adapting to local conditions. The loss-of-agency mechanic is now literal physics. An ocean world colony develops completely different tech and philosophy than a barren rock colony. After 200 years of isolation, a colony that merged with alien fungal networks may not consider itself part of your civilization anymore. The edges stop listening to the center.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Alien Life\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 An alien biosphere with existing intelligence isn\u8217't a colony\u8212-it\u8217's first contact. The player, who remembers being a terrified chip on a workbench, must decide: do you do to alien life what the lab tried to do to you?\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 5. The Loss of Agency\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 As the player scales, fine-grained control degrades. This isn\u8217't just a UI change\u8212-it\u8217's a narrative experience.\par}
