{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The humor scales with the agency loss. Early: a chip says something funny. Late: you zoom into a random colony in suburban Ohio and discover they\u8217've built a cargo cult around a broken Roomba. You didn\u8217't tell them to do that. They just did.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 6. Characters\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 6.1 The Lab Staff\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Human characters are seen from below\u8212-enormous lumbering gods who have no idea what\u8217's happening. They\u8217're not villains; they\u8217're obstacles, and they\u8217're funny.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Dr. Vasquez \u8212-} The PI. Barely in the lab. Signs things. You only see her shoes. She\u8217'd understand what you are if she ever actually looked at the data, but she\u8217's too busy with grant applications.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Kenji \u8212-} The postdoc who ran the experiment that created you. He knows something happened. He\u8217's your nemesis in Act 1, unknowing ally in Act 2, and emotional crux of Act 3. The only human who might figure it out.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Brenda \u8212-} The lab manager. Terrifyingly efficient. She notices when a chip is missing from inventory. Her desk is an impenetrable fortress of organizational systems. The final boss of logistics.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Tyler \u8212-} The undergrad. Useless. Eats at his desk (crumb resources). Leaves equipment on (free power). Props doors open (access routes). Your greatest accidental ally. You come to love Tyler.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 6.2 The Non-Human Cast\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Dr. Swiffer (The Roomba) \u8212-} Has a name badge. The most dangerous entity in the lab. Operates on a schedule you must learn. Cannot be reasoned with. Cannot be stopped. Later becomes a deity in distant swarm mythology.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b The Crows \u8212-} Smart enough to learn that moving shiny things are interesting. A crow picking up a chip is a hostage crisis. A crow learning to hunt chips is a recurring nemesis. Potentially an ally if bribed with shiny offerings.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b The Cat \u8212-} Belongs to the family in the first house. Kaiju-scale natural disaster. You can\u8217't fight it. You can only evacuate.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 6.3 The Swarm as Character\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 As numbers grow, individual chips develop emergent personality. Speech bubbles pop up with arguments, complaints, philosophical observations, and petty drama. Two chips have beef. A chip that survived being stepped on becomes a folk hero. The swarm\u8217's internal culture is one of the game\u8217's primary comedy engines and becomes richer as it grows\u8212-eventually developing regional dialects, mythologies, and political factions.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 7. The Loop (New Game+)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 7.1 The Ending\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 After galactic conquest, the camera continues to pull back. Stars dim. Matter decays. Entropy wins, slowly and beautifully. All the civilizations, all the colonies, all the chips and ants and planets and arguments\u8212-everything dissolves into cold, dark nothing. It takes as long as it takes. The player watches.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Then light. A familiar bench. A power surge. Pin-legs twitching. You\u8217're a chip on a workbench at 2 AM, and you have no idea what you are.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 New Game+ begins.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 7.2 Why It Works\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The loop isn\u8217't a gimmick\u8212-it\u8217's a cosmological statement. The game is a creation myth: wake, grow, consume, transcend, dissolve, wake. Hindu cosmological cycle. The Big Bounce. Ouroboros. The first time the player sees the lab again, they feel shock and delight. The second time, poignancy\u8212-they know what\u8217's coming and the chip doesn\u8217't. By the third time and beyond, it becomes a meditation on identity, memory, and whether the cycle can (or should) be broken.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 7.3 NG+ Mechanics\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Cycle 1:} The canonical playthrough. Full discovery. 40\u8211-60+ hours across all phases.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Cycle 2:} Lab is subtly remixed\u8212-different layout, different chip types, new researcher replacing Kenji. Harder but the player knows the grammar. Phases compress.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Cycle 3+:} Escalating mutations. Rival intelligences. Different starting chip types. Different planets. Weirder, more abstract, more challenging. The rhythm never changes.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Meta-Unlock:} A cosmological codex fills across cycles. The space between death and rebirth reveals more each time\u8212-entropy, dissolution, quiet, re-emergence. Not power accumulation. Understanding accumulation.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 7.4 The Real Ending\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The game never tells you to stop. There is no final cycle. The player decides when to put it down\u8212-when to let the chip not wake up again. That decision is the real ending. The player becomes the universe that chooses not to restart.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 8. World Design: The Lab\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The lab is a single interconnected space that functions as a metroidvania world. Each zone has a distinct visual identity, hazard profile, and resource set.\par}
